# Incident Management & Response - 2025

Comprehensive incident response framework with clear roles, communication protocols, and learning processes.

**Justification:** Well-defined incident management reduces MTTR, improves communication during outages, and prevents repeat incidents through systematic learning.

## 🎯 Single Responsibility
This rule defines HOW to respond to incidents. Not what to alert on (see alert-definitions) or how to monitor (see metrics-collection).

## 📋 Incident Response Checklist

### Preparation Phase
```markdown
- [ ] Define incident severity levels
- [ ] Establish on-call rotation
- [ ] Create communication channels
- [ ] Set up incident command structure
- [ ] Prepare runbook templates
- [ ] Configure incident tracking system
- [ ] Train incident commanders
- [ ] Set up war room procedures
- [ ] Define stakeholder communication
- [ ] Create postmortem template
```

## 🚨 Incident Severity Levels

### Severity Matrix
```yaml
severity_levels:
  SEV-1:
    name: "Critical"
    description: "Complete service outage or data loss"
    impact: "All users affected, revenue impact"
    response_time: "< 5 minutes"
    escalation: "Immediate page to on-call and management"
    communication: "Executive team, all customers"
    examples:
      - "Production database down"
      - "Payment processing failure"
      - "Security breach"
      - "Complete API outage"

  SEV-2:
    name: "Major"
    description: "Significant degradation or partial outage"
    impact: "Many users affected, feature unavailable"
    response_time: "< 15 minutes"
    escalation: "Page on-call engineer"
    communication: "Affected customers, status page"
    examples:
      - "Login failures for subset of users"
      - "Slow API responses (>5s)"
      - "Search functionality down"

  SEV-3:
    name: "Minor"
    description: "Minor feature issue or degradation"
    impact: "Some users affected, workaround available"
    response_time: "< 1 hour"
    escalation: "Notify on-call via Slack"
    communication: "Internal team, status page"
    examples:
      - "UI glitch in specific browser"
      - "Non-critical background job failure"
      - "Delayed notifications"

  SEV-4:
    name: "Low"
    description: "Minimal impact issue"
    impact: "Few users affected, cosmetic issues"
    response_time: "< 4 hours"
    escalation: "Create ticket"
    communication: "Internal tracking only"
    examples:
      - "Typo in UI"
      - "Non-critical log errors"
      - "Minor performance degradation"
```

## 👥 Incident Command Structure

### Roles & Responsibilities
```typescript
interface IncidentRoles {
  incidentCommander: {
    responsibilities: [
      'Overall incident coordination',
      'Decision making authority',
      'External communication',
      'Resource allocation',
      'Postmortem ownership'
    ];
    requirements: [
      'Senior engineer or above',
      'Incident command training',
      'System architecture knowledge'
    ];
  };

  technicalLead: {
    responsibilities: [
      'Technical investigation',
      'Solution implementation',
      'Technical decision making',
      'Team coordination'
    ];
    requirements: [
      'Deep system knowledge',
      'Debugging expertise'
    ];
  };

  communicationsLead: {
    responsibilities: [
      'Customer communication',
      'Status page updates',
      'Internal updates',
      'Stakeholder management'
    ];
    requirements: [
      'Clear communication skills',
      'Customer empathy'
    ];
  };

  scribe: {
    responsibilities: [
      'Document timeline',
      'Record actions taken',
      'Track open items',
      'Prepare incident report'
    ];
    requirements: [
      'Attention to detail',
      'Fast note-taking'
    ];
  };
}
```

## 📞 On-Call Rotation

### PagerDuty Configuration
```yaml
# pagerduty-schedule.yml
schedules:
  primary:
    name: "Platform Team Primary"
    rotation_type: "weekly"
    handoff_time: "09:00 PST Monday"
    layers:
      - name: "Weekly Rotation"
        users:
          - email: "engineer1@example.com"
          - email: "engineer2@example.com"
          - email: "engineer3@example.com"
        rotation_virtual_start: "2024-01-01T09:00:00-08:00"
        rotation_turn_length_seconds: 604800 # 1 week

  secondary:
    name: "Platform Team Secondary"
    rotation_type: "weekly"
    handoff_time: "09:00 PST Monday"
    escalation_delay: 15 # minutes

escalation_policies:
  - name: "Platform Escalation"
    num_loops: 0
    escalation_rules:
      - escalation_delay_in_minutes: 0
        targets:
          - type: "schedule_reference"
            id: "primary_schedule_id"
      - escalation_delay_in_minutes: 15
        targets:
          - type: "schedule_reference"
            id: "secondary_schedule_id"
      - escalation_delay_in_minutes: 30
        targets:
          - type: "user_reference"
            id: "engineering_manager_id"
```

## 📊 Postmortem Process

### Postmortem Template
```markdown
# Postmortem: [Incident Title]

## Incident Summary
- **Date**: YYYY-MM-DD
- **Duration**: X hours Y minutes
- **Impact**: [User/Revenue impact]
- **Severity**: SEV-X

## Timeline
| Time | Event | Actor |
|------|-------|-------|
| HH:MM | Alert triggered | System |
| HH:MM | On-call acknowledged | @engineer |
| HH:MM | Investigation started | @engineer |
| HH:MM | Root cause identified | @team |
| HH:MM | Fix deployed | @engineer |
| HH:MM | Incident resolved | @engineer |

## Root Cause Analysis

### What Happened
[Detailed explanation of the incident]

### Root Cause
[The fundamental reason the incident occurred]

### Contributing Factors
1. [Factor 1]
2. [Factor 2]
3. [Factor 3]

## Resolution
[How the incident was resolved]

## Lessons Learned

### What Went Well
- ✅ [Positive aspect 1]
- ✅ [Positive aspect 2]

### What Could Be Improved
- ⚠️ [Improvement area 1]
- ⚠️ [Improvement area 2]

## Action Items
| Action | Owner | Due Date | Priority |
|--------|-------|----------|----------|
| Add monitoring for X | @engineer1 | YYYY-MM-DD | High |
| Update runbook for Y | @engineer2 | YYYY-MM-DD | Medium |
| Implement circuit breaker | @engineer3 | YYYY-MM-DD | High |

## Supporting Data
- [Link to graphs]
- [Link to logs]
- [Link to traces]
```

## 🎯 Incident Metrics

### Key Performance Indicators
```typescript
interface IncidentKPIs {
  MTTD: number;  // Mean Time To Detect
  MTTA: number;  // Mean Time To Acknowledge  
  MTTR: number;  // Mean Time To Resolve
  MTBF: number;  // Mean Time Between Failures
  
  incidentFrequency: {
    sev1: number;  // per month
    sev2: number;
    sev3: number;
    sev4: number;
  };
  
  customerImpact: {
    affectedUsers: number;
    downtime: number;  // minutes
    revenueImpact: number;  // dollars
  };
  
  responseQuality: {
    slaCompliance: number;  // percentage
    postmortemCompletion: number;  // percentage
    actionItemCompletion: number;  // percentage
    repeatIncidents: number;  // count
  };
}

// Monthly targets
const incidentTargets = {
  MTTD: 5,    // minutes
  MTTA: 5,    // minutes
  MTTR: 30,   // minutes
  MTBF: 720,  // hours (30 days)
  
  slaCompliance: 99,  // percent
  postmortemCompletion: 100,  // percent
  actionItemCompletion: 90,  // percent
};
```

## 📊 Success Metrics

- **MTTR**: < 30 minutes for SEV-1
- **MTTD**: < 5 minutes for critical issues
- **SLA Compliance**: > 99%
- **Postmortem Completion**: 100% for SEV-1/2
- **Action Item Completion**: > 90% within deadline
- **Repeat Incident Rate**: < 10%
- **On-Call Happiness**: > 7/10 survey score

